Founder members of the club have radiated nostalgic pleasure in forming “our own team, owned and run by Africans”, in several conversations I have held with them. Rugby in the early years after independence was decidedly racist.
This is often never spoken about, but top clubs then were owned by whites who openly discriminated against their African compatriots.
“We saw and felt the racism. We were an African country and wanted to assert ourselves. Many of us wondered why Kenyan representative sides were mostly white yet we had many deserving black players who could easily make the team,” Frank Ojiambo, a club legend and one of the founder members of Mwamba told me.
His voice lighting up as he recalled the formation period, Ojiambo said they got a lot of resistance from the rugby establishment that was averse to an African side being formed.



