He says a representative side of African only players called Miro RFC was first formed in 1974 before Mwamba the club was born in 1978.
“It was a true representative of a rugby side from Kenya and was even open to whites. It was exciting and exhilarating for us in those early years. Many top players who had suffered from the discrimination joined us. We were together and shared a common bond,” Ojiambo recalls.
Any player who has played university rugby can attest to this kindred brotherhood. In fact, the bulk of the players who joined this new club were immediate former members of University of Nairobi’s Mean Machine.
They were the same lads, who had won the prestigious Kenya Cup with a swashbuckling Mean Machine side a year earlier in 1977.
They included Absalom “Bimbo” Mutere, prop Couts Otolo, flanker Tom Oketch, winger Shapi Kadir, centre Ben Mukuria, scrum half George Mng’ong’o, who was Mwamba’s inaugural captain.
They were joined by amongst others, eighth man Dennis Awori, previously at Kenya Harlequin, the hard-hitting Ojiambo and flanker Sam “Sky” Akatsa, who had also left Quins.
Nevertheless, the new Mwamba had to find a home first.



