One story that is spoken of in resigned frustration is of a piece of land in South C that Mwamba acquired from the authorities.
The team even started working on the plot, planting grass and trees with the intention of eventually building a rugby facility there only to wake up one morning to find the ground being developed into a residential estate.
But they were happy at Railway Club which was offered for their use by the once prosperous parastatal.
The venue was conveniently located just within walking distance of Nairobi’s CBD, one of the main reasons why yours truly played for the club for one-half season in 1996.
However, it was not all-smooth sailing in as far as having home status at Nairobi Railway. One time Parliament wanted to extend its land to Railways for the honourable members’ use. But that idea died as naturally as it had started.
Mwamba, for one reason or another have also had to temporarily relocate their training to Nairobi School, Upper Hill School, Uhuru Park, South C and so on. Anyway, back to the heady formation years.
Nation rugby writer Jaykhee Carbosh wrote thus in his Kenya Cup season preview of February 25, 1978: “The claim that Mean Machine is the best side in the Kenya Cup will be a challenge for Absalom ‘Bimbo’ Mutere of Mwamba RFC and Rod Evans of Nondies Club, captains of the defending champs’ closest challengers respectively.”



